Halve, peel and chop the @onion{1}(peeled and chopped) into small pieces. Trim the @green beans{80}(trimmed) then chop into thirds. Zest and halve the @lemon{1/2}(zested and halved). Peel and grate the @garlic{2%cloves}(peeled and grated) (or use a #garlic press{}).

Heat a drizzle of @oil{} in a large #frying pan{} over medium to high heat. Once hot, add the @chorizo{60%g} and cook, stirring, until it has released its oils, ~{3%minutes}. Add the onion and cook, stirring, until softened, ~{4-5%minutes}. Add the garlic, half the lemon zest and half the @smoked paprika{1%tsp} and cook, stirring, for ~{1%minute}.

Add the @Arborio rice{175%g} to the pan and stir to coat well. Cook for ~{1%minute}. Add the @chicken stock powder{1} and @water{750%ml} to the pan and season with @salt{} and @pepper{}. Stir to mix, then cover with a #lid{} (or some #foil{}) and cook, stirring occasionally, for ~{20-25%minutes}.

> Add a splash more water if the liquid evaporates and the rice isn't quite cooked.

Meanwhile, heat a drizzle of @oil{} in another frying pan on medium high heat. Add the green beans and cook, stirring, until just tender, ~{4-5%minutes}. Transfer to a #plate{} but do not wash the pan.

Pop the @coley fillet{2} in a #bowl{} with the remaining lemon zest, remaining paprika and a drizzle of @oil{}. Season with @salt{} and @pepper{}. Mix well to coat.

> Wash your hands after handling raw fish.

Return the now empty frying pan to the heat and cook the fish for ~{2-3%minutes} on each side.

> The fish is cooked when opaque in the middle.

Once cooked, transfer the fish to a plate and flake the fish into pieces using two #forks{}.

Once the rice is cooked, carefully stir the flaked coley and green beans through the paella with juice from half the lemon. Cut the remaining lemon into wedges. Taste and add more salt and pepper if you like. Divide between plates and serve with lemon wedges. Enjoy!